								<Item class="LocalScript" referent="RBX51D37C8C068C410F9BD1B9D3D654F97A">
									<Properties>
										<ProtectedString name="Source"><![CDATA[--[[
		  ____            _           _   _ _      _     _ _     
		 |  _ \ _ __ ___ (_) ___  ___| |_(_) | ___| |   (_) |__  
		 | |_) | '__/ _ \| |/ _ \/ __| __| | |/ _ \ |   | | '_ \ 
		 |  __/| | | (_) | |  __/ (__| |_| | |  __/ |___| | |_) |
		 |_|   |_|  \___// |\___|\___|\__|_|_|\___|_____|_|_.__/ 
		               |__/                                      
		
			By VolcanoINC
			Created mid-2015
		
		
		----------------------------------------
		-- INTRODUCTION                       --
		----------------------------------------
		
		The ProjectileLib module is intended for weapons that fire fast-travelling projectiles. The module returns the Projectile
		class, which is outlined in this document.
		
		
		
		----------------------------------------
		-- BEHAVIOR - EXTERNAL BALLISTICS     --
		----------------------------------------
		
		The external ballistics behavior is subject to three basic physical effects: gravity, rotational drift and drag. All of
		these affect the path of the projectile as it travels through empty space.
		
		Gravity accelerates the projectile downwards along the Y axis. How strong this effect is depends on workspace.Gravity, which
		by default is 196.2 studs/second^2.
		
		Rotational drift comes into effect slightly later, when gravity has begun to pull it downwards. The projectile will accelerate
		to the right at 0.05 studs/second^2 for every stud/second that it moves downwards relative to the direction in which it was
		originally fired.
		
		Drag affects the projectile at all times. The projectile will shed 10% of its velocity every second, and there are currently
		no ways to get around this.
		
		The projectile has a maximum life-time of 60 steps per default, and will also be destroyed if its velocity drops below 10
		studs per second.
		
		
		
		----------------------------------------
		-- BEHAVIOR - TERMINAL BALLISTICS     --
		----------------------------------------
		
		The terminal ballistics behavior depends on the angle of incidence (the angle at which the projectile hits a given surface).
		Fast travelling projectiles are more likely to penetrate the material, while slow projectiles are more likely to bounce off.
		The threshhold angle depends on the velocity of the projectile, the angle of incidence and the density of the impacted material.
		
		If the projectile bounces off, it will multiply its velocity by the density of the material divided by 10, and this factor is
		capped at 0.5, meaning the projectile will shed at least 50% of its velocity when bouncing off.
		For example, when the projectile impacts a block of plastic and decides to bounce, it will multiply its velocity by 0.07,
		because the density of plastic is 0.7.
		
		If the projectile penetrates the material, it will calculate the distance it travels inside of that material. If the distance is
		further than the projectile can penetrate the material, the projectile is destroyed. If the maximum distance is greater than the
		distance travelled inside the material, the projectile will re-emerge with reduced velocity. The velocity loss is calculated as
		1000 times the distance multiplied by the density of the material. In other words, the maximum distance the projectile can penetrate 
		is the speed of the projectile divided by 1000 times the density of the material.
		
		The raw formulas for the speed after impact are:
			- Bounce:	Speed = Speed * min(MaterialDensity/10,0.5)
			- Pierce:	Speed = Speed - min(1000*MaterialDensity*DistanceInMaterial,Speed)
			- Stop:		Speed = 0
		
		
		
		----------------------------------------
		-- CONSTRUCTORS                       --
		----------------------------------------
		
		The Projectile class has one constructor:
		
			projectile = Projectile.new(
				Tool,
				Origin,
				Unused,
				Direction,
				Speed,
				RotationalSpeed,
				Damage,
				ForceMultiplier = 1,
				PenetrationMultiplier = 1
			)
		
		The values are:
			- Tool (Instance)					The tool that the projectile was fired from. This is used purely for ignoring 
												instances that should not be hit by the projectile. The parent of this instance 
												is automatically added to the raytrace ignore list.
			
			- Origin (Vector3)					The origin position of the projectile.
			
			- Unused (nil)						Used to be the target position of the projectile, but is no longer in use. Use
												Direction instead.
			
			- Direction (Vector3)				The direction in which the projectile will be fired. It will eventually deviate
												from this direction due to several simulated physical effects.
			
			- Speed (Number)					The speed (in studs per second) that the projectile travels. Realistic values
												range from 1200 (for low brass shotgun shells) to 3000 (for sniper rifles), but 
												values outside of this range are possible and unrestricted.
			
			- RotationalSpeed (Number)			The angular speed of the projectile, in arbitrary units. A RotationalSpeed of 1
												means that the bullet will accelerate to the right by 0.05 studs/sec^2 for every
												stud/second that it travels downwards relative to the original direction it was
												fired. Realistic-feeling values are in the range of 7.5 to 12.5, but values outside
												of this range are possible and unrestricted. The effect scales linearly, and
												negative values are possible.
			
			- Damage (Number)					The amount of damage done to humanoids by the projectile at 100% of its muzzle 
												velocity. Damage scales linearly with velocity. This is subject to change, as the
												damage should also scale with the distance that the projectile travels inside of
												the character.
			
			- ForceMultiplier (Number)			A multiplier for the force the projectile applies to objects on hit. The force is
												this number multiplied by the change in velocity of the projectile, and is applied
												for 0.1 seconds. This argument is optional.
			
			- PenetrationMultiplier (Number)	A multiplier for the distance a projectile can penetrate into materials. The
												default distance is 1 stud through a material with a density of 1 per 1000 studs/sec.
												The effect scales linearly with velocity, density and this multiplier. This argument
												is optional.
		
		
		
		----------------------------------------
		-- METHODS                            --
		----------------------------------------
		
		A Projectile object has the following methods:
		
		- projectile:setTracerEnabled(bool enabled) 	This method disables the orange tracer beam if false is passed.
		- projectile:setLifespan(int lifespan)			Sets the maximum amount of steps that the projectile can exist.
		- projectile:setOnHitCallback(function cback)	Sets a callback function, which is called every time a part is hit.
		- bool = projectile:step(double delta)			Simulates one physics step of the projectile. Returns false if the projectile
														should be destroyed.
		- projectile:Destroy()							Properly destroys the tracer and anything contained within it. Use this instead
														of manually destroying the tracer beams.
		
		
		
		----------------------------------------
		-- ON-HIT CALLBACK                    --
		----------------------------------------
		
		The on-hit callback function is called every time a projectile impacts a BasePart. The callback is wrapped in a coroutine, so it
		behaves more like an event, except that a projectile can only have one callback function. The function is called with the following
		information:
			
			OnHitCallback(
				Part,
				Position,
				Force,
				ImpactType,
				Velocity,
				PEntry,
				PExit
			)
		
		The values are:
			- Part (Instance) 		The part that was hit.
			
			- Position (Vector3)	The position at which the part was hit, in world coordinates.
			
			- Force (Vector3) 		The force applied to the part by the impact
			
			- ImpactType (String)	The type of the impact. Is "Bounce" for ricochet impacts, "Pierce" if the projectile pierced the material, 
									or "Stop" if the material stopped the projectile.
			
			- Velocity (Vector3)	The velocity at which the projectile is travelling after the impact.
			
			- PEntry (Vector3)		The world position of the impact. Only passed if the projectile pierces the material.
			
			- PExit (Vector3)		The world position at which the projectile exits the material. Only passed if the projectile pierces the
									material.
		
		
		
		----------------------------------------
		-- OTHER FUNCTIONS                    --
		----------------------------------------
		
		The following functions are supplied for various purposes that are not part of the above sections.
		
		- Projectile.insertModuleInto(instance parent)		This function parents a clone of the ModuleScript into the specified instance. Useful
															for keeping the module up to date automatically while still being able to use the module
															in LocalScripts.
		
		- Projectile.runHandler()							This function starts a handler for projectiles, which will automatically step projectiles
															so you don't have to do so in your own code. This should be perfectly fine for most
															applications of the simulation. This is done automatically when a projectile using the
															built-in projectile handler is spawned.
]]]]></ProtectedString>
										<bool name="Disabled">true</bool>
